(byebug)
~~~

We can use this prompt to find the issue.
Typing in `@event.errors` yields

~~~bash
#<ActiveModel::Errors:0x007f54fa167258 @base=#<Event id: nil, name: "some name", created_at: nil, updated_at: nil>, @messages={:"address.addressable"=>["must exist"]}, @details={:"address.addressable"=>[{:error=>:blank}]}>
~~~

It appears our address does not know to whom it belongs.
Remember, addressable_id is a foreign key designating who the address belongs_to, in this case an Event.
If it is missing, this belongs_to relationship will be parentless.

Rails 5 recently made the belongs_to association [require a parent by default](http://blog.bigbinary.com/2016/02/15/rails-5-makes-belong-to-association-required-by-default.html), but there seems to be an issue with assignment before saving.
This seems to be a [bug](https://github.com/rails/rails/issues/29781) on Rails part.
It looks like a chicken or egg problem, if you disable this validation it'll save, and if you check for addressable after save finishes you'll find it just fine.

To get around this, you can turn off the Address model's (`app/models/address.rb`) validation check:

~~~ruby
class Address < ApplicationRecord
  belongs_to :addressable, polymorphic: true, optional:true
end
~~~

OR you can leave the validation check on and manually assign addressable in event#create (`app/controllers/events_controller.rb`).
I would go with this option.

~~~ruby
def create
  @event = Event.new(event_params)
  @event.address.addressable = @event #<<<<<<<<<<< ADD THIS
  respond_to do |format|
    if @event.save
      format.html { redirect_to @event, notice: 'Event was successfully created.' }
      format.json { render :show, status: :created, location: @event }
    else
      #dont forget to remove the 'byebug' that was here
      format.html { render :new }
      format.json { render json: @event.errors, status: :unprocessable_entity }
    end
  end
end
~~~

